［Proof］First, assume that when $x$ takes integer values, $f(x)=a x^{2}+b x+c$ is also an integer. Then
(1) $f(0)=c$ is an integer;
(2) $f(1)=a+b+c$ is an integer, hence $a+b=f(1)-c$ is also an integer;
(3) $f(2)=4 a+2 b+c$ is an integer, hence $2 a=f(2)-2(a+b)-c$ is also an integer.

Conversely, if $2 a, a+b, c$ are integers, then for any integer $x, a x^{2}+b x+c$ takes integer values. In fact,
$$
\begin{aligned}
a x^{2}+b x+c & =a x^{2}-a x+a x+b x+c \\
& =a x(x-1)+(a+b) x+c \\
& =2 a \frac{x(x-1)}{2}+(a+b) x+c .
\end{aligned}
$$

Since $x(x-1)$ is the product of two consecutive integers, $\frac{x(x-1)}{2}$ is an integer. Therefore, $a x^{2}+b x+c$ is the sum of three integers, and thus is an integer.

