Since by the condition not all coefficients in the product are divisible by 4, the coefficients of both polynomials cannot all be even. Therefore, at least one of them, for example, the polynomial $B$, has some coefficients that are not even. Suppose that the polynomial $A$ also has some odd coefficients. Consider the first of them (with the smallest index); let this be the coefficient $a_{s}$. Further, let the first odd coefficient of the polynomial $B$ be $b_{k}$. Consider the coefficient of $x^{k+s}$ in the product of the polynomials $A$ and $B$. The degree $x^{k+s}$ in the product could only arise from such degrees of $x$, the sum of whose exponents is $k+s$; therefore, this coefficient is equal to

$$
\begin{aligned}
a_{0} b_{k+s}+a_{1} b_{k+s-1}+\ldots+a_{s-1} b_{k+1} & +a_{s} b_{k}+ \\
& +a_{s+1} b_{k-1}+\ldots+a_{s+k} b_{0}
\end{aligned}
$$

In this sum, all products before the term $a_{s} b_{k}$ are even, since all numbers $a_{0}, a_{1}, \ldots, a_{s-1}$ are even. Also, all products after $a_{s} b_{k}$ are even, since $b_{k-1}, b_{k-2}, \ldots, b_{0}$ are even numbers. The product $a_{s} b_{k}$, however, is an odd number, since both $a_{s}$ and $b_{k}$ are odd numbers. Therefore, the sum is odd, which contradicts the fact that all coefficients in the product are even. Thus, the assumption that the polynomial $A$ has odd coefficients is incorrect, and therefore, all coefficients of $A$ are even numbers. This is what we needed to prove.

