$$
\frac{u_{13}^{2}}{u_{12}^{2}}=\frac{u_{15}^{2}}{u_{13}^{2}}
$$

Taking the square root of both sides of this equation, we get either

$$
\frac{u_{13}}{u_{12}}=\frac{u_{15}}{u_{18}}
$$

or

$$
\frac{u_{13}}{u_{12}}=-\frac{u_{15}}{u_{13}}
$$

Consider the first equation. For any arithmetic progression, $u_{13} = u_{12} + d, u_{15} = u_{13} + 2d = u_{12} + 3d$, where $d$ is the common difference of the progression. Therefore,

$$
\begin{aligned}
\frac{u_{12}+d}{u_{12}} & =\frac{u_{13}+2d}{u_{13}} \\
1+\frac{d}{u_{12}} & =1+\frac{2d}{u_{18}} \\
\frac{d}{u_{12}} & =\frac{2d}{u_{13}}
\end{aligned}
$$

Assume that $d \neq 0$, then

$$
\frac{u_{13}}{u_{12}}=2, \quad \frac{u_{13}^{2}}{u_{12}^{2}}=4
$$

i.e., in this case, the common ratio of the obtained geometric progression is 4.

